data.content:
This is a **C# 14 span overload resolution** breaking change.

## What happened

In C# 14 / .NET 10, `Span<T>` and `ReadOnlySpan<T>` overloads now participate in extension method resolution. When you write `array.Contains(num)` inside an expression tree, the compiler now binds to `MemoryExtensions.Contains` (which takes `ReadOnlySpan<T>`) instead of `Enumerable.Contains` (which takes `IEnumerable<T>`).

Expression trees **cannot represent span-based methods**, so this throws at runtime.

## How to fix

Any of these three approaches work — force the compiler to pick the `Enumerable.Contains` overload:

```csharp
// Option 1: Cast to IEnumerable<T>
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => ((IEnumerable<int>)array).Contains(num);

// Option 2: Use .AsEnumerable()
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => array.AsEnumerable().Contains(num);

// Option 3: Call Enumerable.Contains explicitly
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);
```

The same pattern applies to `Reverse()` on arrays — it now binds to the in-place `MemoryExtensions.Reverse` (returns `void`) instead of `Enumerable.Reverse`. Use `Enumerable.Reverse(arr)` explicitly.
